    <body.head>
      <hedline>
        <hl1>The Missile Shield, Under Fire</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Arnold B Lopez-Cepero letter says most serious problem in deploying limited anti-ballistic missile system lies in computer software systems that have to work flawlessly</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>The most serious problem in deploying the limited anti-ballistic missile system currently being proposed (editorial, April 30) lies in the computer software systems that must ultimately manage such a defensive shield. To be truly effective, they have to work flawlessly the very first time they are used in a tactical situation.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>The most serious problem in deploying the limited anti-ballistic missile system currently being proposed (editorial, April 30) lies in the computer software systems that must ultimately manage such a defensive shield. To be truly effective, they have to work flawlessly the very first time they are used in a tactical situation.</p>
        <p>With several of the recent scientific probes sent to Mars, we have seen that flawless software engineering, even in a much more narrowly focused and technically limited objective, is a goal yet to be fully realized. What is the guarantee that this could be achieved in a much more complex and critical scenario?</p>
        <p>ARNOLD B. LOPEZ-CEPERO  Austin, Tex., May 3, 2000</p>
      </block>
    </body.content>
